w.smh.com.au/national/improving-outcomes-in-aboriginal-health-20130125-2dc1u.html| archive-date=30 Jan 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Mandarin>{{cite web| url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/98384-please-dont-be-bystanders-treaty-commissioner-calls-for-public-support/| title=Please don't be bystanders': treaty commissioner calls for public support| last=Donaldson| first=David| date=10 September 2018| website=themandarin.com.au| access-date=15 October 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015003514/https://www.themandarin.com.au/98384-please-dont-be-bystanders-treaty-commissioner-calls-for-public-support/| archive-date=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=PBAus>{{cite web|url=https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2018/01/vision-culturally-confident-aboriginal-community/| title=A Vision for a Culturally Confident Aboriginal Community| last=Michael| first=Luke| date=29 January 2019| website=probonoaustralia.com.au|access-date=15 October 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129011648/https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2018/01/vision-culturally-confident-aboriginal-community/| archive-date=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=VN2014>{{cite journal| url=https://issuu.com/vaccho/docs/vaccho_autumn_2014_web_abaa451d3a3856| title=Rethinking cancer, Rising Hope Workshop brings leaders together| journal=Vaccho News| page=8| date=Winter 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CancerMOU>{{cite web|url=https://www.cutyourcancerrisk.org.au/blogs/mou_signing.html| title=Having a yarn about bowel cancer - the official launch| date=26 September 2011| website=cutyourcancerrisk.org|access-date=4 November 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104095912/https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.cutyourcancerrisk.org.au/blogs/mou_signing.html| archive-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=GGAO>{{cite web| url=http://old.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2013/Media%20notes%20-%20AO%20(final).pdf| title=Officer (AO) in the General Division of the Order of Australia| website=gg.gov.au| page=14| date=26 January 2013| access-date=5 November 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105012811/http://old.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2013/Media%20notes%20-%20AO%20(final).pdf| archive-date=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kick>{{cite web| url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/kicking-the-habit-of-a-lifetime-20081212-6xkq.html| title=Kicking the habit of a lifetime| last=Miller| first=Nick| date=13 January 2008| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| location=[[Sydney]], [[Australia]]| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122003731/https://www.smh.com.au/national/kicking-the-habit-of-a-lifetime-20081212-6xkq.html| archive-date=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wheeler>{{cite web| url=https://www.wheelercentre.com/people/jill-gallagher| title=Jill Gallagher| website=wheelercentre.com| access-date=22 November 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122013911/https://www.wheelercentre.com/people/jill-gallagher|archive-date=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=VHRW>{{cite web| url=https://whise.org.au/assets/docs/policy/Victorian%20Honour%20Roll%20of%20Women%202001-%202011.pdf| title=VICTORIAN HONOUR ROLL OF WOMEN List of Inductees 2001 to 2011| website=whise.org.au| access-date=22 November 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218002129/http://whise.org.au/assets/docs/policy/Victorian%20Honour%20Roll%20of%20Women%202001-%202011.pdf|archive-date=18 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!------Unused Refs----------------\n\n<ref name=MBC>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37194869/murray_black_collection/| title=Relics Act puts Walker off-side with academics| last=Birnbauer| first=Bill| date=14 September 1984| page=10| work=The Age| location=Melbourne| access-date=15 October 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014220241/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37194869/murray_black_collection/| archive-date=14 October 2019||via=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Vision>{{cite web| url=https://cv.vic.gov.au/stories/aboriginal-culture/the-koorie-heritage-trust-collections-and-history/the-vision-for-a-trust/| title=The vision for a Trust| website=cv.vic.gov.au| access-date=15 October 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015042806/https://cv.vic.gov.au/stories/aboriginal-culture/the-koorie-heritage-trust-collections-and-history/the-vision-for-a-trust/| archive-date=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Garwood>{{cite web| url=https://www.aboriginalvictoria.vic.gov.au/terry-garwood| title=Terry Garwood| website=aboriginalvictoria.vic.gov.au| access-date=15 October 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015064854/https://www.aboriginalvictoria.vic.gov.au/terry-garwood| archive-date=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n-----------------End Unused Refs------------------>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vaccho.org.au Victorian Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation]\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Jillian}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Aboriginal peoples of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Australian women chief executives]]\n[[Category:People from Canberra]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Australian indigenous rights activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian community activist}}\n<!--*****************************************************************\n    *  Please use template {{R|\"ref name\"}} when citing references, *\n    *   and insert reference code within {{{{Reflist|30em|refs=}}   *\n    *                 template under references heading.            *\n    *****************************************************************-->\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jill Gallagher AO\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1955}} \n| birth_place   = [[Canberra]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Australia]]n, [[Portland, Victoria#Indigenous Gunditjmara People|Gunditjmara]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = CEO Victorian Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| awards        = [[Order of Australia#Officer (AO)|Officer of the Order of Australia]]\n}}\n\n'''Jill Gallagher''' [[Officer of the Order of Australia|AO]] (born 1955) is a [[Portland, Victoria#Indigenous Gunditjmara People|Gunditjmara]] woman from Australia who has been the Chief Executive Officer of the Victorian Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation (VACCHO) since 2001.  As a single mother in her twenties Gallagher was accepted into a training scheme for young Aboriginal people at the [[Museums Victoria|Museum of Victoria]].  She worked on the return of the Murray Black Collection and served as manager of the heritage branch of [[Aboriginal Affairs Victoria|Minister for Aboriginal Affairs (Victoria)]] before taking up a position at VACCHO in 1998.  In 2017 Gallagher was appointed Commissioner of the [[2019 Victorian First Peoples' Assembly election|Victorian Treaty Advancement Commission]] until the voting period ended in October 2019.  Gallagher was inducted into the [[Victorian Honour Roll of Women]] in 2009 and the Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll in 2015. She was made an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] in 2013.\n\n==Early life==\n\nGallagher was born in 1955, one of 10 children, in the [[Australian Capital Territory]], principally recognised as [[Ngunnawal]] Country.  Her mother was a [[Portland, Victoria#Indigenous Gunditjmara People|Gunditjmara]] woman and a father of [[Ireland|Irish]] decent.  Gallagher's father died in an accident when she was a baby.{{R|AbHonRoll}}\n\nWork available to Aboriginal people was limited and Gallagher's mother travelled extensively for seasonal work picking vegetables.{{R|TheAgeSharedPride}} Gallagher spent much of her early childhood in [[Gunai]]kurnai country, [[Gippsland]], her community revolved around the seasonal camps inhabited by other seasonal workers.{{R|IndXDJ}}\n\nIn 1963 Gallagher's family moved to [[Collingwood, Victoria|Collingwood]] on [[Wurundjeri]] Country, where her mother found work in a box factory.  Gallagher graduated from the George Street [[Education in Australia#Primary schools|Primary School]] after attending 13 different schools, and continued her education at the Fitzroy Girls' [[Education in Australia#Secondary schools|School]].  She was rebellious and clashed with teachers and left school at the age of 14 and ran away from home, living on the streets before returning home and commencing work in a factory.{{R|AbHonRoll}}\n\nEarly memories include living in a camp on [[Braiakaulung people|Braiakaulung]] country on the [[Avon River (Gippsland, Victoria)|Avon River]] at [[Stratford, Victoria|Stratford]] dotted by the glow of dozens of campfires,{{R|IndXDJ}} and her mother being asked to leave a whites only hotel in [[Warnambool]].{{R|TheAgeSharedPride}}\n\n==Career==\n\nIn her early twenties, and a single mother, Gallagher regretted leaving school at an early age.  She applied for, and was accepted into a training scheme for Aboriginal young people at the [[Museums Victoria|Museum of Victoria]].{{R|AbHonRoll}}   She took up a position at the [[Victoria Archaeological Survey]], which offered her the opportunity to learn about Aboriginal history including culture, language and the devastating effect of European settlement had on Aboriginal people. She took on a role as manager of the heritage branch of Aboriginal Affairs Victoria which enabled her to pass her knowledge on to young people.{{R|AbHonRoll}} While with Museums Victoria Gallagher worked on the return of the Murray Black Collection,{{efn|name=MurrayBlack}} to Aboriginal communities in northern [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and Southern [[New South Wales]].  Gallagher continues to serve on the National Committee for the Repatriation of Skeletal Remains.{{R|SMHImproving}}\n\nIn 1998 Gallagher took a position at the Victorian Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation (VACCHO),{{efn|name=fnVACCHO}} and in 2001 she became its [[Chief executive officer|CEO]].  Gallagher quickly recognised tobacco as a major cause of health problems within the Aboriginal community and, in 2008, gave up smoking after 40 years.  She actively encouraged VACCO employees and each Aboriginal health organisation in Victoria to develop a stop smoking campaign and to become smoke free.  The idea was to provide leadership in aboriginal communities, and reduce the burden on a stretched health services.{{R|Kick}}\n\nAs CEO of VACCHO Gallagher obtained bi-partisan support from the Victorian Government for the statement of intent to close the 17 year life expectancy gap between indigenous and non-indigenous Australians.  The statement was signed in 2008 by Victorian [[Premier]] [[John Brumby]].  She lists this as one of her most significant achievements as CEO of VACCHO{{R|SMHImproving|Wheeler}}\n\nIn January 2018 Gallagher took 18 months leave of absence from VACCHO when she was appointed Commissioner of the [[2019 Victorian First Peoples' Assembly election|Victorian Treaty Advancement Commission]].{{R|PBAus}}  The commission was set up to create an Aboriginal representative body to establish rules for future treaty negotiations with the Victorian Government.{{R|Mandarin}} The commission will be wound up once the representative body is formed.\n\nIn 2009 Gallagher was diagnosed with stage 4 bowel cancer which had spread to her liver and diaphragm.  She had 2 surgeries and chemotherapy and has used her experience to promote cancer awareness in the Aboriginal community.{{R|VN2014|CancerMOU}}\n\nGallagher has served on a number of State government and statutory advisory committees including; the Victorian Early Childhood Development Advisory Committee, the Equal Opportunity Commission Victoria Indigenous Reference Group, the Child Death Review, the Cooperative Research Centre on Aboriginal Health, and the Premiers Aboriginal Advisory Committee.{{R|AbHonRoll}}\n\nGallagher has cited mentors Jim Berg{{efn|name=fnBerg}} of the [[Koorie Heritage Trust]] and Terry Garwood{{efn|name=fnGarwood}} of [[Minister for Aboriginal Affairs (Victoria)|Aboriginal Affairs Victoria]] as great influencers, but is inspired mostly by her mother for her resilience and determination in the face of the hardship she endured.{{R|AbHonRoll}}\n\n==Awards==\n\n*Victorian Honour Roll for Women inductee 2009{{R|VHRW}}\n*Officer of the Order of Australia 2013 ''\"For distinguished service to the indigenous community of Victoria, through leadership in the area of health and contributions to cultural, welfare and professional organisations.\"''{{R|GGAO|SMHAO}}\n*Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll inductee 2015.{{R|AbHonRoll}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Aboriginal Australians]]\n* [[Indigenous health in Australia]]\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{notelist|30em|refs=\n\n{{efn|name=MurrayBlack| The Murray Black Collection is a collection of 800 Aboriginal skeletal remains estimated to be 10,000 to 14,000 years old.  The remains were held by the [[University of Melbourne]] and were transferred to the custody of Museums Victoria for return to their burial grounds along the [[Murray River]], after the Aboriginal Legal Service took action in the [[Supreme Court of Victoria|Supreme Court]].}}\n\n{{efn|name=fnVACCHO| VACCHO is the peak body representing and advocating for the community controlled Aboriginal health services in Victoria}}\n\n{{efn|name=fnBerg|Jim Berg is a [[Dhauwurd Wurrung|Gunditjmara]] man, he is an artist and was the CEO of the Victorian Aboriginal Legal Service when he founded the Victorian Aboriginal Cultural Heritage Trust in the mid 1980's.  He was instrumental in the repatriation of the Murray Black Collection.}}\n\n{{efn|name=fnGarwood | Terry Garwood is a [[Yorta Yorta|Yorta]], [[Wemba-Wemba|Wemba Wemba]] and [[Wergaia]] man.  He is a career Victorian public servant, during his time at Aboriginal Affairs Victoria his key work included co-ordinating Victoria's responses to the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody and the National Inquiry into the Forced Removal of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Children from their Families.  He ensured that Victoria co-operated fully with the [[Stolen Generations|stolen generation enquiry]].}}\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em||refs=\n\n<ref name=AbHonRoll>{{cite web| url=https://www.vic.gov.au/aboriginalvictoria/community-engagement/leadership-programs/aboriginal-honour-roll/2015-victorian-aboriginal-honour-roll/jill-gallagher-ao.html| title=Jill Gallagher AO| website=vic.gov.au| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315123632/https://www.vic.gov.au/aboriginalvictoria/community-engagement/leadership-programs/aboriginal-honour-roll/2015-victorian-aboriginal-honour-roll/jill-gallagher-ao.html| archive-date=13 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=IndXDJ>{{cite web| url=https://indigenousx.com.au/daniel-james-jill-gallagher-and-the-road-ahead-for-victorias-treaty/| title=Jill Gallagher and the road ahead for Victoria's Treaty| last=James| first=Daniel| website=indigenousx.com.au| date=9 July 2018| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012032327/https://indigenousx.com.au/daniel-james-jill-gallagher-and-th